Great question — this is a classic gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, a new DI scope is created automatically per HTTP request, so `AddScoped<MyDbContext>()` gives you a fresh instance per request.

**In MAUI, there is no per-request scope.** The app has a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` lives for the entire app lifetime, accumulating tracked entities across navigations.

### Fixes

**Option 1 — Use `AddTransient`:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();
```
Each injection gets a new instance. Simple, but you lose shared-instance-within-a-unit-of-work semantics.

**Option 2 — Use `IServiceScopeFactory` to create manual scopes:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddScoped<MyDbContext>();

// In your page/viewmodel:
public class MyViewModel
{
    private readonly IServiceScopeFactory _scopeFactory;

    public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)
        => _scopeFactory = scopeFactory;

    public async Task LoadData()
    {
        using var scope = _scopeFactory.CreateScope();
        var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
        // db is scoped to this block and disposed at the end
    }
}
```
This is the closest equivalent to ASP.NET Core's per-request scoping — you control exactly when the scope (and `DbContext`) begins and ends.

**TL;DR:** MAUI has no automatic scope boundary like HTTP requests. Use `AddTransient` for simplicity, or manually create scopes with `IServiceScopeFactory` for finer control.
